<font color="#FF0000">THE FACTS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec  1  2:37:20 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
It was Jim Riddle, not Mr. Parson, who compared himself and other soldiers to &quot;unthinking cattle&quot;. He says &quot;My country called and I served without question...It is not my place to decide what was right or wrong&quot;. Of course it was his place to decide what's right or wrong. You should not kill large numbers of people &quot;without question&quot; just because you were &quot;called&quot; and told to do so. Before you extol blind worship of the American government and whatever they do, let me point out what they've done. Your beloved government arranged a coup d'etat in Chile and overthrew the first democratically elected leader in that country. The American government trained the death squads of El Salvador which massacred whole villages and targeted Catholic clergy. The American government broke American laws and sold weapons to Iranian terrorists for the purpose of perpetuating a rebellion in Nicaragua. All of this we did in the name of &quot;fighting Communism&quot;. Are these the actions of a country that cares about human rights? If the American government cared about democracy then why did we support dictators such as Marcos or Noreiga? Why do we support monarchies such as Saudi Arabia and Kuwait? The reason our leaders got away with all of these things is because of people like Jim Riddle who support whatever our government does &quot;without question&quot; and feel it's not their place to decide what's right or wrong. To blindly support the polices that led to the deaths of so many Americans and didn't benefit the United States or anyone else, and then accuse others of being &quot;self-righteous&quot; is the ultimate hypocrisy. The reason the United States was against the Soviet Union was the same reason why the Soviet Union was against the United States. They both sought world domination. It's what existed in previous centuries between Britain and France, Rome and Carthage, and Athens and Sparta.  
